In what looked like response to the apprehension generated ahead of the sit-at-home order by pro-Biafran groups for May 31, Enugu Police Commissioner, Mohammed Aliyu, has met with transport, market, youths and students leaders in the state. In the meeting at the command headquarters, the CP said it was in pursuance of the recently launched Operation Restore Peace in the Southeast Geopolitical Zone by the Inspector-General of Police, Alkali Baba Usman. He spoke to the leaders and other law-abiding citizens of the state on the needs for sustained support to the command, in its bid to professionally stabilize security order in the state through the operation. Aliyu therefore urged the citizenry to remain law-abiding and go about their lawful businesses without fear of intimidation or harassment while promptly reporting suspected criminals and their activities to the nearest police station. The CPâ€™s meeting was contained in a statement by Enugu spokesman, Daniel Ndukwe. According to the release, the police boss solicited sustained support from the citizenry, while reaffirming commitment to collaboratively attain goals of Operation RP and urging residents to go about their lawful businesses without fear of intimidation or harassment. The Commissioner used the opportunity of the meeting to further acquaint them with the purpose of the Operation which, among other things, is to stabilize security order and restore the Southeast zone to its historical pride of place, where its highly respected people are known to be peaceful, tolerant, innovative, industrious and entrepreneurial. He also reaffirmed commitment to collaborate with sister security agencies and law-abiding citizens to maximally attain goals of the operation in the state, in view of emerging security challenges.